{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509844"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:20:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:20:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11449"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11449"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.27,0.34,0.17,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51014"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4083"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11449"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36258"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1491"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6033"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47252"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51014"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman on the spinal rehabilitation ward requires review due to sudden significant hypertension of 160/120 mmHg (usually 130/70 mmHg). The patient states she has a \u0027pounding headache\u0027 and worsening abdominal pain. She appears very diaphoretic and anxious. She has not passed stool for five days and has a history of peripheral vascular disease and chronic bronchitis. She was part of a shooting accident four weeks prior which lead to a spinal cord transection at the level of T6. Her pulse rate is 57/min. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn further examination, the patient has a grossly distended abdomen, feels cool to touch and has a functioning IDC present. Her head is raised, her legs lowered and any restrictive clothing is removed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Unblock the catheter","Aperients","GTN patch","Amlodipine","Antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u0027s spinal cord trauma and sudden presentation of symptoms and signs, it is highly likely this patient has developed autonomic dysreflexia. Autonomic dysreflexia (also known as autonomic hyperreflexia) is a medical emergency which affects individuals with a spinal cord injury typically at the level of T6 or above. Sympathetic nervous system stimulation below the level of the spinal cord injury leads widespread vasoconstriction of splanchnic blood vessels, resulting in severe hypertension (due to release of substances such as noradrenaline). Once sensed by the aortic arch and carotid body baroreceptors, parasympathetic activity above the level of the lesion occurs causing compensatory bradycardia, but the inhibitory brain stem impulses fail to travel below the lesion. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA systolic blood pressure increase of over 20mm Hg from their resting levels requires ongoing monitoring and assessment for resolution, and a systolic blood pressure greater than 150mm Hg requires medical review and consideration of pharmacological treatment.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EDelayed treatment of autonomic dysreflexia can lead to many serious complications including stroke, seizures, pulmonary oedema, myocardial infarction and death. Common causes typically involve the urinary system (distended bladder, urinary tract infection, kidney stones), bowels (constipation, impaction, haemorrhoids or gaseous distention), skin (burns, tight clothing, infection), and then other causes including fracture, sexual intercourse, labour or severe menstrual cramping.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EInitial treatment of autonomic dysreflexia involves conservative interventions of raising the patients head and feet in attempt to lower BP, loosen constrictive clothing, check bladder draining for obstruction, monitor blood pressure every two minutes and ask the patient or carer if they suspect a cause. If a cause can not be readily identified, then antihypertensive medication should be commenced concurrently with the search for the cause. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the significant hypertension, this is the most important aspect to correct due to its risk of subsequent haemodynamic compromise. As such, pharmaceutical measures such as \u003Cstrong\u003EGTN (glyceryl trinitrate)\u003C/strong\u003E can provide immediate relief and lower blood pressures to safer levels. Alternatively, if a GTN patch, spray or tablet is not available or contraindicated then an alternative short acting, rapid acting antihypertensive agent can be used such as captopril. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EGiven this patient\u0027s history and physical examination, it is likely that this patient has an impacted bowel or constipation that has caused the new onset autonomic dysreflexia. Typically involving \u003Cstrong\u003Eaperients\u003C/strong\u003E with a low \u0027time to effect\u0027 such as an enema, or a per rectal examination with local anaesthetic to manually dis impact the stool. However, treatment of the bowel impaction should only be initiated once the patient is haemodynamically stable, as administering \u003Cstrong\u003Eaperients \u003C/strong\u003Esuch as an enema can further precipitate hypertension, which may risk a hypertensive crisis.\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EAdditionally, per rectal examination should be considered with caution as it can exacerbate autonomic dysreflexia. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EIf a blocked catheter is suspected, then \u003Cstrong\u003Eunblocking the catheter\u003C/strong\u003E and irrigating the bladder is required. Otherwise, remove the catheter and reinsert it after 2-3 minutes in attempt to empty the bladder, but beware for sudden hypotension. This is not suspected in this patient as his bladder is not distended and the IDC is functional. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E (or other calcium channel blockers) are typically used to treat hypertension, but due to its \u0027time to effect\u0027 being approximately eight hours, GTN is a better choice in this context (time to effect is within a few minutes). \u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotic\u003C/strong\u003E treatment may be useful in treating bacterial cause of autonomic dysreflexia such as a UTI, however this patient does not have a fever and an UTI is not suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autonomic dysreflexia is a medical emergency involving high sympathetic stimulation leading to hypertension and blockage of compensatory parasympathetic stimulation below the level of a spinal cord injury (typically T6) (1, 2).","If a cause for autonomic dysreflexia can not be readily found, then administration of an antihypertensive agent such as GTN should be given concurrently with investigations for the cause.","To treat bowel impaction causing autonomic dysreflexia, manual disimpaction or administration of aperents is essential managing the patients symptoms."],"references":["NSW Agency for Clinical Innovation. Treatment of autonomic dysreflexia for adults and adolescents with spinal cord injuries: A guide for clinicians in non-specialist units. Sydney: Agency for Clinical Innovation; June 2024.","Allen KJ, Leslie SW. Autonomic Dysreflexia. [Updated 2022 Feb 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482434/","Coggrave, M.J. \u0026 Norton, C., 2010. The need for manual evacuation and oral laxatives in the management of neurogenic bowel dysfunction after spinal cord injury: a randomized controlled trial of a stepwise protocol. Spinal cord, 48(6), pp.504\u2013510."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36258"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11449"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36258"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-20T11:20:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-20T11:22:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4083"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51014"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null